source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-3629
Reason: The target compound is a complex heterocyclic molecule which includes various functional groups contributing to the melting point. We will assess each group and provide an increment or decrement relative to a basic structure such as benzene which has a melting point of 5.5°C. Pyridine, a basic heterocycle, has a higher melting point (around 115°C) than benzene due to the presence of a nitrogen atom that introduces a level of polarity and offers potential for hydrogen bonding. Each additional pyridine ring is expected to raise the melting point further, though by a diminishing increment as steric effects become more pronounced and the molecule becomes bulkier. Estimate +60°C for each of two additional pyridine rings. The triazolothiadiazine core is a dense heterocyclic system which generally increases melting point due to rigid structure and increased molecular weight; estimated at +80°C. Sulfur in thiadiazine contributes to the molecular weight and polarity increasing the melting point; estimate +40°C. Overall structure complexity and intermolecular forces would elevate the melting point even further, but for the sake of this estimation, the complexity increment is not strictly quantified.
Prediction: 5.5 (benzene) + 60 (first pyridine ring) + 60 (second pyridine ring) + 80 (triazolothiadiazine core) + 40 (sulfur in thiadiazine) = 245.5°C
